Note:
This file handles dominance analysis and dominance tree computation.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process dominance analysis and dominance tree construction
- Handle dominance frontier computation and dominance validation
- Manage dominance optimization and dominance-based analysis
- Process dominance verification and dominance tree verification

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Dominance analysis enables SSA construction and loop optimization
- Proper dominance handling ensures correct dominance tree computation
- Dominance analysis support enables Runa compilation for dominance-based optimization

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Dominance analysis and dominance tree construction
- Dominance frontier computation and dominance validation
- Dominance optimization and dominance-based analysis
- Dominance verification and dominance tree verification
:End Note

Note: ============================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================
Note: DATA STRUCTURES
Note: ============================================================

Type called "DominanceTreeNode":
    @Reasoning
    Represents a node in the dominance tree.
    The dominance tree is a rooted tree where:
    - The root is the entry block
    - The parent of each node is its immediate dominator
    - Children of a node are the blocks it immediately dominates

    This structure enables efficient dominance queries by traversing
    the tree structure rather than recomputing relationships.
    @End Reasoning

    block_id as Integer           Note: Block this node represents
    idom as Integer               Note: Immediate dominator block ID (-1 if entry)
    children as Integer           Note: List of dominated block IDs (TIER 3)
    child_count as Integer        Note: Number of children
    dom_level as Integer          Note: Distance from entry in dominance tree
End Type

Type called "DominanceFrontierSet":
    @Reasoning
    Stores the dominance frontier for a single block.

    The dominance frontier DF(B) is the set of blocks where B's dominance "stops":
    - B dominates a predecessor of each block in DF(B)
    - B does not strictly dominate any block in DF(B)

    Dominance frontiers are critical for SSA construction:
    phi nodes are placed at the dominance frontiers of definition blocks.
    @End Reasoning

    block_id as Integer           Note: Block whose frontier this represents
    frontier_blocks as Integer    Note: List of block IDs in the frontier (TIER 3)
    frontier_count as Integer     Note: Number of blocks in frontier
End Type

Type called "DominanceInfo":
    @Reasoning
    Complete dominance analysis result for a CFG.
    This structure caches all dominance-related information to avoid recomputation.

    Invalidation: When the CFG is modified (blocks added/removed, edges changed),
    this structure must be invalidated and recomputed.
    @End Reasoning

    cfg as Integer                     Note: Pointer to MIRCFG
    entry_block_id as Integer          Note: Entry block ID
    dom_tree as Integer                Note: List of DominanceTreeNode (TIER 3)
    node_count as Integer              Note: Number of nodes in dominance tree
    frontiers as Integer               Note: List of DominanceFrontierSet (TIER 3)
    frontier_count as Integer          Note: Number of frontier sets
    is_valid as Integer                Note: Boolean: analysis is current
    postorder as Integer               Note: List of block IDs in postorder (TIER 3)
    postorder_count as Integer         Note: Number of blocks in postorder
    reverse_postorder as Integer       Note: List of block IDs in RPO (TIER 3)
    rpo_count as Integer               Note: Number of blocks in RPO
    block_to_rpo_index as Integer      Note: Map: block_id -> RPO index (TIER 3)
End Type

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHASE 1: DATA STRUCTURES bitwise and FOUNDATION
Note: ============================================================

Process called "create_dominance_info" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates and initializes a DominanceInfo structure.

    Memory layout (TIER 3 OWNED HEAP - 80 bytes):
    - offset 0:  cfg pointer (8 bytes)
    - offset 8:  entry_block_id (8 bytes)
    - offset 16: dom_tree pointer (8 bytes)
    - offset 24: node_count (8 bytes)
    - offset 32: frontiers pointer (8 bytes)
    - offset 40: frontier_count (8 bytes)
    - offset 48: is_valid (8 bytes)
    - offset 56: postorder pointer (8 bytes)
    - offset 64: postorder_count (8 bytes)
    - offset 72: reverse_postorder pointer (8 bytes)
    - offset 80: rpo_count (8 bytes)
    - offset 88: block_to_rpo_index pointer (8 bytes)
    Total: 96 bytes
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Uses TIER 3 allocation for permanent lifetime during CFG analysis.
    All list pointers initialized to 0 (will be allocated separately).
    @End Implementation

    Note: Allocate DominanceInfo structure (96 bytes)
    Let info_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 96

    Note: Initialize fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 0, cfg_ptr

    Note: Get entry block ID
    Let entry_id be proc get_cfg_entry_block_id from CFG with cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 8, entry_id

    Note: Initialize list pointers to 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16, 0 Note: dom_tree
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24, 0 Note: node_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 32, 0 Note: frontiers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 40, 0 Note: frontier_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 48, 0 Note: is_valid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 56, 0 Note: postorder
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 64, 0 Note: postorder_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 72, 0 Note: reverse_postorder
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 80, 0 Note: rpo_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 88, 0 Note: block_to_rpo_index

    Return info_ptr
End Process

Process called "compute_postorder_traversal" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, entry_block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes postorder traversal of the CFG using depth-first search.

    Postorder traversal visits nodes AFTER visiting all descendants:
    - Visit all children first (recursive DFS)
    - Then visit the current node
    - Results in ordering where successors appear before predecessors

    Reverse postorder (obtained by reversing this) has the property:
    - Predecessors appear before successors (except back edges)
    - Critical for efficient iterative dataflow algorithms
    - Cooper algorithm converges quickly with RPO iteration order

    Algorithm:
    1. Maintain visited set to avoid cycles
    2. DFS from entry block
    3. Append to postorder list AFTER visiting children
    4. Return postorder list

    Time complexity: O(V + E) where V = blocks, E = edges
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Uses iterative DFS with explicit stack to avoid recursion depth issues.
    Stack contains (block_id, phase) pairs:
    - phase 0: First visit (push children)
    - phase 1: Second visit (add to postorder)
    @End Implementation

    Note: Create visited set (using List as set - contains block IDs)
    Let visited be proc create from List

    Note: Create postorder result list
    Let postorder be proc create from List

    Note: Create DFS stack (contains block_id values)
    Let stack be proc create from List

    Note: Create phase stack (0 = first visit, 1 = second visit)
    Let phase_stack be proc create from List

    Note: Push entry block with phase 0
    proc append from List with stack, entry_block_id
    proc append from List with phase_stack, 0

    Note: DFS traversal
    While proc length from List with stack is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop from stack
        Let stack_len be proc length from List with stack
        Let block_id be proc get from List with stack, stack_len minus 1
        Let phase be proc get from List with phase_stack, stack_len minus 1

        Note: Remove from stacks (simulate pop)
        Let new_stack be proc create from List
        Let new_phase_stack be proc create from List
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than stack_len minus 1:
            Let val be proc get from List with stack, i
            proc append from List with new_stack, val
            Let ph be proc get from List with phase_stack, i
            proc append from List with new_phase_stack, ph
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set stack to new_stack
        Set phase_stack to new_phase_stack

        If phase equals 0:
            Note: First visit - check if already visited
            If proc contains from List with visited, block_id equals 1:
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Mark as visited
            proc append from List with visited, block_id

            Note: Push block again with phase 1 (for postorder addition)
            proc append from List with stack, block_id
            proc append from List with phase_stack, 1

            Note: Push all successors with phase 0
            Let block_ptr be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
            If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Let successors be proc get_block_successors from CFG with block_ptr
                Let succ_count be proc get_block_successor_count from CFG with block_ptr
                Let j be 0
                While j is less than succ_count:
                    Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, j
                    If proc contains from List with visited, succ_id equals 0:
                        proc append from List with stack, succ_id
                        proc append from List with phase_stack, 0
                    End If
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            Otherwise:
            Note: Second visit - add to postorder
            proc append from List with postorder, block_id
        End If
    End While

    Note: Cleanup visited set
    proc destroy from List with visited

    Return postorder
End Process

Process called "compute_reverse_postorder" that takes postorder as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reverses the postorder list to produce reverse postorder (RPO).

    RPO has the critical property for iterative dataflow:
    - Blocks are visited in an order where predecessors come before successors
    - Except for back edges (loop backedges)
    - Enables fast convergence of iterative algorithms (typically 2-3 iterations)

    Implementation: Simply reverse the postorder list.
    Time complexity: O(n) where n = number of blocks
    @End Reasoning

    Let postorder_len be proc length from List with postorder
    Let rpo be proc create from List

    Note: Reverse the postorder list
    Let i be postorder_len minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with postorder, i
        proc append from List with rpo, block_id
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return rpo
End Process

Process called "create_block_to_rpo_index_map" that takes rpo as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates a mapping from block_id to its index in the RPO list.

    This enables O(1) lookup of RPO position, needed for:
    - Finding first processed predecessor in Cooper algorithm
    - Determining if an edge is a back edge (target RPO < or equal to source RPO)

    Representation: List where index = block_id, value = RPO index
    For sparse block IDs, we use -1 to indicate "not in RPO"
    @End Reasoning

    Let rpo_len be proc length from List with rpo

    Note: Find maximum block ID to size the map
    Let max_block_id be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than rpo_len:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with rpo, i
        If block_id is greater than max_block_id:
            Set max_block_id to block_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create map (list of size max_block_id + 1)
    Let map be proc create from List
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than or equal to max_block_id:
        proc append from List with map, -1 Note: -1 means "not in RPO"
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Populate map with RPO indices
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than rpo_len:
        Set block_id to proc get from List with rpo, i
        proc set from List with map, block_id, i
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return map
End Process

Process called "find_common_dominator" that takes block1_id as Integer, block2_id as Integer, idom_map as Integer, rpo_index_map as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Finds the common dominator of two blocks by traversing dominator chains.

    This is the "intersect" operation in Cooper's algorithm.

    Algorithm:
    1. Start with finger1 = block1, finger2 = block2
    2. While fingers don't match:
       - If finger1 has higher RPO index (later in RPO), move it to its idom
       - If finger2 has higher RPO index, move it to its idom
    3. When fingers match, that's the common dominator

    Correctness: The first common ancestor in the dominator tree
    is the common dominator. RPO ordering ensures we find it efficiently.

    Time complexity: O(depth of dom tree) = O(n) worst case
    @End Reasoning

    Let finger1 be block1_id
    Let finger2 be block2_id

    Note: Traverse dominator chains until they meet
    While finger1 is not equal to finger2:
        Note: Get RPO indices
        Let rpo1 be proc get from List with rpo_index_map, finger1
        Let rpo2 be proc get from List with rpo_index_map, finger2

        Note: Move the finger with higher RPO index up the dom tree
        If rpo1 is greater than rpo2:
            Note: finger1 is later in RPO, move to its idom
            Let idom1 be proc get from List with idom_map, finger1
            If idom1 equals -1:
                Note: No idom yet, return finger2
                Return finger2
            End If
            Set finger1 to idom1
        Otherwise:
            Note: finger2 is later in RPO, move to its idom
            Let idom2 be proc get from List with idom_map, finger2
            If idom2 equals -1:
                Note: No idom yet, return finger1
                Return finger1
            End If
            Set finger2 to idom2
        End If
    End While

    Note: Fingers met at common dominator
    Return finger1
End Process

Process called "compute_dominance_tree" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the dominance tree for a CFG using the Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy algorithm.

    **COOPER-HARVEY-KENNEDY ALGORITHM (2001):**

    This is the industry-standard algorithm for dominance analysis, used in
    LLVM, GCC, and other production compilers. It's simple, fast, and correct.

    **Algorithm Overview:**
    1. Compute reverse postorder (RPO) traversal of CFG
    2. Initialize idom[entry] = entry, all others = undefined (-1)
    3. Iterate until convergence:
       - For each block b in RPO (except entry):
         - new_idom = first processed predecessor
         - For each other predecessor p:
           - If idom[p] is defined:
             - new_idom = intersect(p, new_idom)
         - If idom[b] ≠ new_idom:
           - idom[b] = new_idom
           - changed = true
    4. Repeat until no changes (typically 2-3 iterations)

    **Why RPO Order is Critical:**
    - RPO ensures predecessors are processed before successors (except back edges)
    - This means most idom values are correct on first iteration
    - Back edges are handled correctly by the intersect operation
    - Fast convergence: O(iterations × blocks) ≈ O(2n) typically

    **Time Complexity:**
    - Best case: O(V + E) for reducible CFGs (2 iterations)
    - Worst case: O(V²) for irreducible CFGs (many iterations)
    - Typical case: O(V + E) with 2-3 iterations

    **Correctness:**
    - Proven correct for all CFGs (reducible and irreducible)
    - Computes immediate dominators exactly
    - See Cooper et al. 2001 paper for formal proof
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Immediate dominator map uses direct-indexed List for O(1) lookup:
    idom_map[block_id] = immediate_dominator_id

    This is the standard production implementation (used in LLVM, GCC):
    - O(1) access time for idom queries
    - Cache-friendly sequential memory layout
    - Minimal memory overhead (one entry per block)
    - -1 represents "undefined" (entry block or unreachable)

    No Dictionary needed - block IDs are dense integers, making
    List indexing the optimal choice for this use case.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Create DominanceInfo structure
    Let info_ptr be create_dominance_info(cfg_ptr)
    Let entry_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 8

    Note: Step 1: Compute postorder and reverse postorder
    Let postorder be compute_postorder_traversal(cfg_ptr, entry_id)
    Let postorder_count be proc length from List with postorder
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 56, postorder
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 64, postorder_count

    Let rpo be compute_reverse_postorder(postorder)
    Let rpo_count be proc length from List with rpo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 72, rpo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 80, rpo_count

    Note: Create block_id -> RPO index map
    Let rpo_index_map be create_block_to_rpo_index_map(rpo)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 88, rpo_index_map

    Note: Step 2: Initialize idom map
    Note: Find maximum block ID to size the map
    Let blocks_list be proc get_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Let block_count be proc get_cfg_block_count from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Let max_block_id be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Let block_id be proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        If block_id is greater than max_block_id:
            Set max_block_id to block_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create idom map (list of size max_block_id + 1)
    Let idom_map be proc create from List
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than or equal to max_block_id:
        proc append from List with idom_map, -1 Note: -1 means "undefined"
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initialize idom[entry] = entry
    proc set from List with idom_map, entry_id, entry_id

    Note: Step 3: Iterate until convergence
    Let changed be 1
    Let iteration_count be 0
    Let max_iterations be 100  Note: Safety limit

    While changed equals 1 and iteration_count is less than max_iterations:
        Set changed to 0
        Set iteration_count to iteration_count plus 1

        Note: For each block in RPO (except entry)
        Let rpo_idx be 0
        While rpo_idx is less than rpo_count:
            Set block_id to proc get from List with rpo, rpo_idx

            Note: Skip entry block
            If block_id equals entry_id:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Get block's predecessors
            Set block_ptr to proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
            If block_ptr equals 0:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with block_ptr
            Let pred_count be proc get_block_predecessor_count from CFG with block_ptr

            Note: Find first processed predecessor
            Let new_idom be -1
            Let pred_idx be 0
            While pred_idx is less than pred_count:
                Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, pred_idx
                Let pred_idom be proc get from List with idom_map, pred_id

                If pred_idom is not equal to -1:
                    Note: This predecessor has been processed
                    Set new_idom to pred_id
                    Set pred_idx to pred_count  Note: Break loop
                End If

                Set pred_idx to pred_idx plus 1
            End While

            Note: If no processed predecessor found, skip this block
            If new_idom equals -1:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Intersect with all other processed predecessors
            Set pred_idx to 0
            While pred_idx is less than pred_count:
                Set pred_id to proc get from List with predecessors, pred_idx
                Set pred_idom to proc get from List with idom_map, pred_id

                Note: Skip if same as new_idom or not processed
                If pred_id is not equal to new_idom and pred_idom is not equal to -1:
                    Note: Intersect: find common dominator
                    Set new_idom to find_common_dominator(pred_id, new_idom, idom_map, rpo_index_map)
                End If

                Set pred_idx to pred_idx plus 1
            End While

            Note: Update idom if changed
            Let current_idom be proc get from List with idom_map, block_id
            If current_idom is not equal to new_idom:
                proc set from List with idom_map, block_id, new_idom
                Set changed to 1
            End If

            Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Note: Step 4: Store idom results in MIRBasicBlock.dominator fields
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        Let idom_id be proc get from List with idom_map, block_id

        Note: Store in block's dominator field
        proc set_block_dominator from CFG with block_ptr, idom_id

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 5: Build DominanceTreeNode structures
    Let dom_tree be proc create from List

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        Set idom_id to proc get from List with idom_map, block_id

        Note: Create DominanceTreeNode (40 bytes)
        Note: Layout: block_id(0), idom(8), children(16), child_count(24), dom_level(32)
        Let node_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 40
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0, block_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8, idom_id

        Let children_list be proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 16, children_list
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 24, 0 Note: child_count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 32, 0 Note: dom_level (computed later)

        proc append from List with dom_tree, node_ptr

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Build parent-child relationships
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set node_ptr to proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Set block_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0
        Set idom_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8

        Note: Skip entry block (its idom is itself)
        If block_id equals entry_id:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Find parent node and add this block as a child
        Set j to 0
        While j is less than block_count:
            Let parent_node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, j
            Let parent_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 0

            If parent_block_id equals idom_id:
                Note: Found parent, add child
                Let parent_children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 16
                proc append from List with parent_children, block_id

                Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 24
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 24, child_count plus 1

                Set j to block_count  Note: Break loop
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Store dominance tree in DominanceInfo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16, dom_tree
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24, block_count

    Note: Mark as valid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 48, 1

    Note: Set dominance_computed flag in CFG
    proc set_cfg_dominance_computed from CFG with cfg_ptr, 1

    Note: Cleanup idom_map
    proc destroy from List with idom_map

    Return info_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHASE 2: DOMINANCE QUERIES
Note: ============================================================

Process called "get_immediate_dominator" that takes info_ptr as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the immediate dominator of a given block.

    The immediate dominator (idom) of block B is the unique block that:
    1. Strictly dominates B (dominates B and idom ≠ B)
    2. Does not strictly dominate any other strict dominator of B

    In other words, idom is B's parent in the dominance tree.

    For the entry block, idom = entry (conventionally idom[entry] = entry).

    Time complexity: O(n) to search dominance tree
    Can be optimized with block_id -> node_ptr map if needed.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Get dominance tree
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    If dom_tree equals 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24

    Note: Find node for this block_id
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Let node_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0

        If node_block_id equals block_id:
            Note: Found node, return its idom
            Let idom_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8
            Return idom_id
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Block not found in dominance tree
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "dominates" that takes info_ptr as Integer, dominator_id as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Checks if dominator_id dominates block_id.

    Block A dominates block B if every path from the entry block to B
    passes through A.

    Algorithm:
    1. If dominator_id == block_id, return true (block dominates itself)
    2. Walk up the dominator chain from block_id:
       - If we reach dominator_id, return true
       - If we reach entry (idom[entry] = entry), return false

    Time complexity: O(depth of dominance tree) = O(n) worst case

    Returns: 1 if dominates, 0 otherwise
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: A block dominates itself
    If dominator_id equals block_id:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Walk up the dominator chain from block_id
    Let current_id be block_id
    Let entry_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 8
    Let max_iterations be 1000  Note: Safety limit to prevent infinite loops

    Let iteration be 0
    While iteration is less than max_iterations:
        Note: Get immediate dominator of current block
        Let idom_id be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, current_id)

        If idom_id equals -1:
            Note: No dominator, reached root or invalid block
            Return 0
        End If

        If idom_id equals dominator_id:
            Note: Found dominator in chain
            Return 1
        End If

        If idom_id equals current_id:
            Note: Reached entry block (idom[entry] = entry)
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Move up the chain
        Set current_id to idom_id
        Set iteration to iteration plus 1
    End While

    Note: Safety limit reached (shouldn't happen in valid dominance tree)
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "strictly_dominates" that takes info_ptr as Integer, dominator_id as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Checks if dominator_id strictly dominates block_id.

    Block A strictly dominates block B if:
    1. A dominates B
    2. A ≠ B

    This is used in many compiler algorithms that need to distinguish
    between a block dominating itself vs. dominating others.

    Time complexity: O(depth of dominance tree)

    Returns: 1 if strictly dominates, 0 otherwise
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Strict dominance requires A ≠ B
    If dominator_id equals block_id:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Otherwise, same as regular dominance
    Return dominates(info_ptr, dominator_id, block_id)
End Process

Process called "get_dominated_blocks" that takes info_ptr as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a list of all blocks dominated by the given block.

    Algorithm:
    1. Find the node for block_id in the dominance tree
    2. Perform DFS traversal from that node
    3. Collect all descendant nodes (children, grandchildren, etc.)

    This includes block_id itself (a block dominates itself).

    Time complexity: O(n) where n = number of dominated blocks
    Space complexity: O(n) for result list

    Returns: List of block IDs (TIER 3), or empty list if block not found
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Create result list
    Let result be proc create from List

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Get dominance tree
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    If dom_tree equals 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24

    Note: Add block_id itself (block dominates itself)
    proc append from List with result, block_id

    Note: Find node for block_id
    Let root_node_ptr be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Let node_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0

        If node_block_id equals block_id:
            Set root_node_ptr to node_ptr
            Set i to node_count  Note: Break loop
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: If block not found, return list with just block_id
    If root_node_ptr equals 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Note: DFS traversal from root_node to collect all descendants
    Let stack be proc create from List
    proc append from List with stack, root_node_ptr

    While proc length from List with stack is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop from stack
        Let stack_len be proc length from List with stack
        Let current_node_ptr be proc get from List with stack, stack_len minus 1

        Note: Remove from stack (simulate pop)
        Let new_stack be proc create from List
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than stack_len minus 1:
            Let node be proc get from List with stack, j
            proc append from List with new_stack, node
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set stack to new_stack

        Note: Get children of current node
        Let children_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_node_ptr, 16
        Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current_node_ptr, 24

        Note: Add each child to result and push to stack
        Let child_idx be 0
        While child_idx is less than child_count:
            Let child_block_id be proc get from List with children_list, child_idx
            proc append from List with result, child_block_id

            Note: Find child node in dom_tree and push to stack
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than node_count:
                Let child_node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, k
                Let child_node_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_node_ptr, 0

                If child_node_block_id equals child_block_id:
                    proc append from List with stack, child_node_ptr
                    Set k to node_count  Note: Break inner loop
                End If

                Set k to k plus 1
            End While

            Set child_idx to child_idx plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Note: Cleanup stack
    proc destroy from List with stack

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHASE 3: DOMINANCE FRONTIERS
Note: ============================================================

Process called "compute_dominance_frontiers" that takes info_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the dominance frontier for every block in the CFG.

    **DOMINANCE FRONTIER DEFINITION:**
    The dominance frontier DF(X) of block X is the set of all blocks Y such that:
    1. X dominates a predecessor of Y
    2. X does not strictly dominate Y

    In other words, DF(X) contains the blocks where X's dominance "stops" -
    blocks that are just outside X's dominance region.

    **CRITICAL FOR SSA CONSTRUCTION:**
    Dominance frontiers determine where to place phi nodes:
    - When variable V is defined in block X, a phi node for V is needed
      at every block in DF(X)
    - This is because paths that go through X and paths that don't go through X
      converge at DF(X), requiring a phi node to merge values

    **ALGORITHM (Cytron et al. 1991):**
    For each block B with multiple predecessors:
        For each predecessor P of B:
            runner = P
            While runner ≠ idom[B]:
                DF[runner] = DF[runner] ∪ {B}
                runner = idom[runner]

    **INTUITION:**
    - Start at each predecessor P of a join point B
    - Walk up the dominator tree from P
    - Stop when we reach B's immediate dominator
    - All blocks visited on this walk have B in their dominance frontier

    **WHY THIS WORKS:**
    - If P is a predecessor of B, then P dominates itself and can reach B
    - As we walk up from P toward idom[B], each block on the path can reach B
    - These blocks don't strictly dominate B (else we'd have passed idom[B])
    - Therefore B is in the dominance frontier of each block on the path

    **TIME COMPLEXITY:**
    - O(E × depth) where E = edges, depth = dominance tree depth
    - Typical case: O(E) for CFGs with shallow dominance trees
    - Worst case: O(V × E) for deeply nested control flow

    **SPACE COMPLEXITY:**
    - O(V²) worst case if every block is in every frontier
    - Typical: O(V) or O(V log V) for structured control flow

    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Creates DominanceFrontierSet for each block and stores in DominanceInfo.
    Uses List data structures for frontier sets (dynamic sizing).
    @End Implementation

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get CFG and dominance tree
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 0
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24

    If cfg_ptr equals 0 or dom_tree equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get all blocks from CFG
    Let blocks_list be proc get_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Let block_count be proc get_cfg_block_count from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Note: Find maximum block ID for frontier map sizing
    Let max_block_id be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Let block_id be proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        If block_id is greater than max_block_id:
            Set max_block_id to block_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create frontier map (list of Lists, indexed by block_id)
    Note: frontier_map[block_id] = List of block IDs in that block's frontier
    Let frontier_map be proc create from List
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than or equal to max_block_id:
        Let frontier_list be proc create from List
        proc append from List with frontier_map, frontier_list
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute dominance frontiers using Cytron algorithm
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with block_ptr
        Let pred_count be proc get_block_predecessor_count from CFG with block_ptr

        Note: Only process blocks with multiple predecessors (join points)
        If pred_count is greater than 1:
            Note: For each predecessor of this block
            Let pred_idx be 0
            While pred_idx is less than pred_count:
                Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, pred_idx

                Note: Walk up dominator tree from predecessor
                Let runner be pred_id
                Let block_idom be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, block_id)
                Let max_iterations be 1000  Note: Safety limit

                Let iteration be 0
                While runner is not equal to block_idom and iteration is less than max_iterations:
                    Note: Add block_id to runner's dominance frontier
                    Let runner_frontier be proc get from List with frontier_map, runner

                    Note: Check if block_id already in frontier (avoid duplicates)
                    If proc contains from List with runner_frontier, block_id equals 0:
                        proc append from List with runner_frontier, block_id
                    End If

                    Note: Move up to runner's immediate dominator
                    Let runner_idom be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, runner)

                    Note: Stop if we've reached the root or an invalid state
                    If runner_idom equals -1 or runner_idom equals runner:
                        Set runner to block_idom  Note: Force exit
                    Otherwise:
                        Set runner to runner_idom
                    End If

                    Set iteration to iteration plus 1
                End While

                Set pred_idx to pred_idx plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Build DominanceFrontierSet structures
    Let frontier_sets be proc create from List

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        Set frontier_list to proc get from List with frontier_map, block_id
        Let frontier_count be proc length from List with frontier_list

        Note: Create DominanceFrontierSet (24 bytes)
        Note: Layout: block_id(0), frontier_blocks(8), frontier_count(16)
        Let frontier_set_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 0, block_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 8, frontier_list
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 16, frontier_count

        proc append from List with frontier_sets, frontier_set_ptr

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Store frontier sets in DominanceInfo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 32, frontier_sets
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 40, block_count

    Note: Cleanup frontier_map (but keep the frontier lists - they're referenced)
    proc destroy from List with frontier_map

    Return 1  Note: Success
End Process

Process called "get_dominance_frontier" that takes info_ptr as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the dominance frontier set for a specific block.

    The returned list contains the block IDs that are in the dominance frontier
    of the given block. This is used during SSA construction to determine where
    to place phi nodes.

    Time complexity: O(n) to search frontier sets
    Can be optimized with block_id -> frontier_set_ptr map if needed.

    Returns: List of block IDs in the frontier (TIER 3), or empty list if not found
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Let empty be proc create from List
        Return empty
    End If

    Note: Get frontier sets
    Let frontier_sets be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 32
    If frontier_sets equals 0:
        Set empty to proc create from List
        Return empty
    End If

    Let frontier_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 40

    Note: Find frontier set for this block_id
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than frontier_count:
        Let frontier_set_ptr be proc get from List with frontier_sets, i
        Let set_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 0

        If set_block_id equals block_id:
            Note: Found frontier set, return the frontier blocks list
            Let frontier_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 8
            Return frontier_blocks
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Block not found, return empty list
    Set empty to proc create from List
    Return empty
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHASE 4: POST-DOMINANCE
Note: ============================================================

Type called "PostDominanceInfo":
    @Reasoning
    Post-dominance information for a CFG.

    Post-dominance is the reverse of dominance:
    - Block X post-dominates block Y if every path from Y to EXIT passes through X
    - Used for control dependence analysis
    - Used for some optimizations (dead store elimination, etc.)

    The post-dominator tree is similar to the dominator tree but rooted at EXIT.
    @End Reasoning

    cfg as Integer                      Note: Pointer to MIRCFG
    exit_block_id as Integer            Note: Exit block ID
    post_dom_tree as Integer            Note: List of DominanceTreeNode (TIER 3)
    node_count as Integer               Note: Number of nodes in post-dom tree
    is_valid as Integer                 Note: Boolean: analysis is current
    reverse_postorder as Integer        Note: List of block IDs in RPO from exit (TIER 3)
    rpo_count as Integer                Note: Number of blocks in RPO
    block_to_rpo_index as Integer       Note: Map: block_id -> RPO index (TIER 3)
End Type

Process called "compute_reverse_cfg_postorder" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, exit_block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes postorder traversal of the REVERSE CFG starting from exit block.

    Reverse CFG means we traverse predecessors instead of successors:
    - Normal CFG: follow successor edges (forward control flow)
    - Reverse CFG: follow predecessor edges (backward control flow)

    This is needed for post-dominance analysis, which operates on the reverse CFG.

    Algorithm: Same as normal postorder, but traverse predecessors instead of successors.

    Time complexity: O(V + E)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Uses iterative DFS with explicit stack, traversing predecessors instead of successors.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Create visited set
    Let visited be proc create from List

    Note: Create postorder result list
    Let postorder be proc create from List

    Note: Create DFS stack
    Let stack be proc create from List

    Note: Create phase stack (0 = first visit, 1 = second visit)
    Let phase_stack be proc create from List

    Note: Push exit block with phase 0
    proc append from List with stack, exit_block_id
    proc append from List with phase_stack, 0

    Note: DFS traversal (following predecessors instead of successors)
    While proc length from List with stack is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop from stack
        Let stack_len be proc length from List with stack
        Let block_id be proc get from List with stack, stack_len minus 1
        Let phase be proc get from List with phase_stack, stack_len minus 1

        Note: Remove from stacks (simulate pop)
        Let new_stack be proc create from List
        Let new_phase_stack be proc create from List
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than stack_len minus 1:
            Let val be proc get from List with stack, i
            proc append from List with new_stack, val
            Let ph be proc get from List with phase_stack, i
            proc append from List with new_phase_stack, ph
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set stack to new_stack
        Set phase_stack to new_phase_stack

        If phase equals 0:
            Note: First visit - check if already visited
            If proc contains from List with visited, block_id equals 1:
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Mark as visited
            proc append from List with visited, block_id

            Note: Push block again with phase 1 (for postorder addition)
            proc append from List with stack, block_id
            proc append from List with phase_stack, 1

            Note: Push all PREDECESSORS with phase 0 (reverse CFG traversal)
            Let block_ptr be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
            If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with block_ptr
                Let pred_count be proc get_block_predecessor_count from CFG with block_ptr
                Let j be 0
                While j is less than pred_count:
                    Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, j
                    If proc contains from List with visited, pred_id equals 0:
                        proc append from List with stack, pred_id
                        proc append from List with phase_stack, 0
                    End If
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            Otherwise:
            Note: Second visit - add to postorder
            proc append from List with postorder, block_id
        End If
    End While

    Note: Cleanup visited set
    proc destroy from List with visited

    Return postorder
End Process

Process called "compute_post_dominance_tree" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the post-dominance tree for a CFG.

    **POST-DOMINANCE DEFINITION:**
    Block X post-dominates block Y if every path from Y to EXIT passes through X.

    **ALGORITHM:**
    Same as Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy for dominance, but:
    1. Start from EXIT block instead of ENTRY block
    2. Traverse reverse CFG (predecessors instead of successors)
    3. Use reverse postorder from EXIT

    **APPLICATIONS:**
    - Control dependence analysis (for parallelization, debugging)
    - Dead store elimination (if store post-dominates all uses)
    - Understanding which code "must" execute after a given point

    **TIME COMPLEXITY:** Same as dominance - O(V + E) typical, O(V²) worst case

    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Creates PostDominanceInfo structure with post-dominator tree.
    Stores immediate post-dominators in a separate structure (not in MIRBasicBlock).
    @End Implementation

    Note: Null check
    If cfg_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get exit block (or create virtual exit if multiple exits)
    Let exit_block_id be proc get_cfg_exit_block_id from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Let using_virtual_exit be 0

    If exit_block_id equals -1:
        Note: No single exit block - create virtual exit node
        Note: Virtual exit has ID of max_block_id + 1
        Let blocks_list be proc get_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
        Let block_count be proc get_cfg_block_count from CFG with cfg_ptr

        Note: Find maximum block ID
        Let max_block_id be 0
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than block_count:
            Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks_list, i
            Let block_id be proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
            If block_id is greater than max_block_id:
                Set max_block_id to block_id
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Virtual exit ID = max_block_id + 1
        Set exit_block_id to max_block_id plus 1
        Set using_virtual_exit to 1

        Display "compute_post_dominance_tree: created virtual exit node with ID " joined with exit_block_id
    End If

    Note: Allocate PostDominanceInfo structure (64 bytes)
    Note: Layout: cfg(0), exit_id(8), post_dom_tree(16), node_count(24),
    Note:         is_valid(32), rpo(40), rpo_count(48), block_to_rpo(56)
    Let post_info_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 0, cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 8, exit_block_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 16, 0 Note: post_dom_tree
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 24, 0 Note: node_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 32, 0 Note: is_valid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 40, 0 Note: rpo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 48, 0 Note: rpo_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 56, 0 Note: block_to_rpo_index

    Note: Step 1: Compute reverse CFG postorder and RPO
    Let postorder be compute_reverse_cfg_postorder(cfg_ptr, exit_block_id)
    Let rpo be compute_reverse_postorder(postorder)
    Let rpo_count be proc length from List with rpo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 40, rpo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 48, rpo_count

    Note: Create block_id -> RPO index map
    Let rpo_index_map be create_block_to_rpo_index_map(rpo)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 56, rpo_index_map

    Note: Step 2: Initialize post-idom map
    Set blocks_list to proc get_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Set block_count to proc get_cfg_block_count from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Set max_block_id to 0
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        If block_id is greater than max_block_id:
            Set max_block_id to block_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create post-idom map
    Let post_idom_map be proc create from List
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than or equal to max_block_id:
        proc append from List with post_idom_map, -1 Note: -1 means "undefined"
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initialize post-idom[exit] = exit
    proc set from List with post_idom_map, exit_block_id, exit_block_id

    Note: Step 3: Cooper algorithm on reverse CFG (iterate until convergence)
    Let changed be 1
    Let iteration_count be 0
    Let max_iterations be 100

    While changed equals 1 and iteration_count is less than max_iterations:
        Set changed to 0
        Set iteration_count to iteration_count plus 1

        Note: For each block in RPO (except exit)
        Let rpo_idx be 0
        While rpo_idx is less than rpo_count:
            Set block_id to proc get from List with rpo, rpo_idx

            Note: Skip exit block
            If block_id equals exit_block_id:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Get block's SUCCESSORS (for post-dominance, successors are "predecessors" in reverse CFG)
            Set block_ptr to proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
            If block_ptr equals 0:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Let successors be proc get_block_successors from CFG with block_ptr
            Let succ_count be proc get_block_successor_count from CFG with block_ptr

            Note: Find first processed successor
            Let new_post_idom be -1
            Let succ_idx be 0
            While succ_idx is less than succ_count:
                Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, succ_idx
                Let succ_post_idom be proc get from List with post_idom_map, succ_id

                If succ_post_idom is not equal to -1:
                    Note: This successor has been processed
                    Set new_post_idom to succ_id
                    Set succ_idx to succ_count  Note: Break loop
                End If

                Set succ_idx to succ_idx plus 1
            End While

            Note: If no processed successor found, skip this block
            If new_post_idom equals -1:
                Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Intersect with all other processed successors
            Set succ_idx to 0
            While succ_idx is less than succ_count:
                Set succ_id to proc get from List with successors, succ_idx
                Set succ_post_idom to proc get from List with post_idom_map, succ_id

                Note: Skip if same as new_post_idom or not processed
                If succ_id is not equal to new_post_idom and succ_post_idom is not equal to -1:
                    Note: Intersect: find common post-dominator
                    Set new_post_idom to find_common_dominator(succ_id, new_post_idom, post_idom_map, rpo_index_map)
                End If

                Set succ_idx to succ_idx plus 1
            End While

            Note: Update post-idom if changed
            Let current_post_idom be proc get from List with post_idom_map, block_id
            If current_post_idom is not equal to new_post_idom:
                proc set from List with post_idom_map, block_id, new_post_idom
                Set changed to 1
            End If

            Set rpo_idx to rpo_idx plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Note: Step 4: Build PostDominanceTreeNode structures
    Let post_dom_tree be proc create from List

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set block_ptr to proc get from List with blocks_list, i
        Set block_id to proc get_block_id from CFG with block_ptr
        Let post_idom_id be proc get from List with post_idom_map, block_id

        Note: Create DominanceTreeNode for post-dominance (reuse structure)
        Let node_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 40
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0, block_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8, post_idom_id

        Let children_list be proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 16, children_list
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 24, 0 Note: child_count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 32, 0 Note: dom_level

        proc append from List with post_dom_tree, node_ptr

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Build parent-child relationships in post-dom tree
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Set node_ptr to proc get from List with post_dom_tree, i
        Set block_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0
        Set post_idom_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8

        Note: Skip exit block
        If block_id equals exit_block_id:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Find parent node and add this block as a child
        Set j to 0
        While j is less than block_count:
            Let parent_node_ptr be proc get from List with post_dom_tree, j
            Let parent_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 0

            If parent_block_id equals post_idom_id:
                Note: Found parent, add child
                Let parent_children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 16
                proc append from List with parent_children, block_id

                Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 24
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent_node_ptr, 24, child_count plus 1

                Set j to block_count  Note: Break loop
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Store post-dominance tree in PostDominanceInfo
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 16, post_dom_tree
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 24, block_count

    Note: Mark as valid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 32, 1

    Note: Cleanup post_idom_map and postorder
    proc destroy from List with post_idom_map
    proc destroy from List with postorder

    Return post_info_ptr
End Process

Process called "get_post_dominator" that takes post_info_ptr as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the immediate post-dominator of a given block.

    The immediate post-dominator of block B is the unique block that:
    1. Post-dominates B
    2. Does not post-dominate any other post-dominator of B

    For the exit block, post-idom[exit] = exit.

    Time complexity: O(n) to search post-dom tree
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If post_info_ptr equals 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Get post-dominance tree
    Let post_dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 16
    If post_dom_tree equals 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 24

    Note: Find node for this block_id
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get from List with post_dom_tree, i
        Let node_block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0

        If node_block_id equals block_id:
            Note: Found node, return its post-idom
            Let post_idom_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8
            Return post_idom_id
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Block not found in post-dominance tree
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "post_dominates" that takes post_info_ptr as Integer, post_dom_id as Integer, block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Checks if post_dom_id post-dominates block_id.

    Block X post-dominates block Y if every path from Y to EXIT passes through X.

    Algorithm: Same as dominates(), but using post-dominance tree.

    Returns: 1 if post-dominates, 0 otherwise
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If post_info_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: A block post-dominates itself
    If post_dom_id equals block_id:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Walk up the post-dominator chain from block_id
    Let current_id be block_id
    Let exit_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with post_info_ptr, 8
    Let max_iterations be 1000

    Let iteration be 0
    While iteration is less than max_iterations:
        Note: Get immediate post-dominator of current block
        Let post_idom_id be get_post_dominator(post_info_ptr, current_id)

        If post_idom_id equals -1:
            Note: No post-dominator, reached root or invalid block
            Return 0
        End If

        If post_idom_id equals post_dom_id:
            Note: Found post-dominator in chain
            Return 1
        End If

        If post_idom_id equals current_id:
            Note: Reached exit block (post-idom[exit] = exit)
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Move up the chain
        Set current_id to post_idom_id
        Set iteration to iteration plus 1
    End While

    Note: Safety limit reached
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PHASE 5: VALIDATION bitwise and DEBUG
Note: ============================================================

Process called "validate_dominance_tree" that takes info_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Validates the dominance tree structure for correctness.

    **DOMINANCE TREE INVARIANTS:**
    1. Entry block has no dominator (or idom[entry] = entry)
    2. Every other block has exactly one immediate dominator
    3. The dominator tree is acyclic (no cycles)
    4. If A dominates B and B dominates C, then A dominates C (transitivity)
    5. Every block (except entry) is reachable via dominance from entry

    **VALIDATION CHECKS:**
    - Entry block check: idom[entry] = entry
    - All blocks have valid idom (not -1, except entry)
    - No cycles in dominator chains
    - Parent-child relationships are consistent
    - Dominance frontiers are consistent with dominance tree

    Returns: 1 if valid, 0 if invalid (prints error message)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Performs comprehensive validation of dominance tree structure.
    Checks for common errors: cycles, missing dominators, inconsistent relationships.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: null info_ptr"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if dominance info is valid
    Let is_valid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 48
    If is_valid equals 0:
        Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: dominance info is marked invalid"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get dominance tree and entry block
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24
    Let entry_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 8

    If dom_tree equals 0 or node_count equals 0:
        Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: empty dominance tree"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check 1: Entry block has idom = entry
    Let entry_idom be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, entry_id)
    If entry_idom is not equal to entry_id:
        Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: entry block idom incorrect"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check 2: All non-entry blocks have valid idom
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Let block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0
        Let idom_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8

        Note: Skip entry block
        If block_id equals entry_id:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Non-entry blocks must have valid idom
        If idom_id equals -1:
            Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: block has no idom"
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check 3: No cycles in dominator chains
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Set node_ptr to proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Set block_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0

        Note: Walk up dominator chain, should reach entry
        Let current be block_id
        Let visited_count be 0
        Let max_visits be node_count plus 1

        While visited_count is less than max_visits:
            Let current_idom be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, current)

            If current_idom equals -1:
                Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: invalid idom in chain"
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Reached entry (idom[entry] = entry)
            If current_idom equals current:
                Note: Should be entry block
                If current is not equal to entry_id:
                    Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: non-entry block has self-idom"
                    Return 0
                End If
                Set visited_count to max_visits  Note: Exit loop (valid)
            Otherwise:
                Set current to current_idom
                Set visited_count to visited_count plus 1
            End If
        End While

        Note: If we hit max_visits, there's a cycle
        If visited_count equals max_visits minus 1:
            Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: cycle detected in dominator chain"
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check 4: Parent-child relationships are consistent
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Set node_ptr to proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Set block_id to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0
        Let children_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 16
        Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 24

        Note: For each child, verify that block_id is its idom
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than child_count:
            Let child_id be proc get from List with children_list, j
            Let child_idom be get_immediate_dominator(info_ptr, child_id)

            If child_idom is not equal to block_id:
                Display "ERROR: validate_dominance_tree: parent-child relationship inconsistent"
                Return 0
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: All validation checks passed
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "print_dominance_tree" that takes info_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Prints the dominance tree for debugging and visualization.

    Output format:
    - Block ID: idom = X, children = [Y, Z, ...]
    - Indented tree structure showing dominance relationships
    - Dominance frontier for each block

    Useful for debugging dominance analysis and understanding
    control flow structure.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Display "ERROR: print_dominance_tree: null info_ptr"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get dominance tree
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24
    Let entry_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 8

    If dom_tree equals 0:
        Display "Dominance tree is empty"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Print header
    Display "============================================================"
    Display "DOMINANCE TREE"
    Display "============================================================"

    Note: Print entry block ID
    Display "Entry block: " continuing
    Display entry_id
    Display ""

    Note: Print each node's information
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, i
        Let block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 0
        Let idom_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 8
        Let children_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 16
        Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 24

        Note: Print block ID
        Display "Block " continuing
        Display block_id continuing
        Display ":"

        Note: Print immediate dominator
        Display "  idom = " continuing
        If idom_id equals block_id:
            Display "ENTRY (self)"
        Otherwise:
            Display idom_id
        End If

        Note: Print children
        Display "  children = [" continuing
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than child_count:
            Let child_id be proc get from List with children_list, j
            Display child_id continuing
            If j is less than child_count minus 1:
                Display ", " continuing
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Display "]"

        Note: Print dominance frontier if available
        Let frontier_blocks be get_dominance_frontier(info_ptr, block_id)
        Let frontier_count be proc length from List with frontier_blocks
        If frontier_count is greater than 0:
            Display "  DF = {" continuing
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than frontier_count:
                Let frontier_block be proc get from List with frontier_blocks, k
                Display frontier_block continuing
                If k is less than frontier_count minus 1:
                    Display ", " continuing
                End If
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
            Display "}"
        Otherwise:
            Display "  DF = {}"
        End If

        Display ""

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Display "============================================================"

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "invalidate_dominance_info" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Invalidates dominance information when the CFG is modified.

    **WHEN TO CALL THIS:**
    - After adding or removing blocks from the CFG
    - After adding or removing edges from the CFG
    - After any transformation that changes control flow structure

    **WHAT IT DOES:**
    - Sets the dominance_computed flag to 0 in the MIRCFG
    - Marks the is_valid flag to 0 in DominanceInfo (if it exists)
    - Forces recomputation of dominance on next use

    **WHY THIS IS NECESSARY:**
    Dominance information is only valid for a specific CFG structure.
    Any modification invalidates the cached dominance tree and frontiers.

    Time complexity: O(1)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If cfg_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Clear dominance_computed flag in CFG
    proc set_cfg_dominance_computed from CFG with cfg_ptr, 0

    Note: Success
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "destroy_dominance_info" that takes info_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Deallocates a DominanceInfo structure and all its associated data.

    **CLEANUP REQUIRED:**
    - Free all DominanceTreeNode structures
    - Free all children lists in tree nodes
    - Free all DominanceFrontierSet structures
    - Free all frontier block lists
    - Free postorder and RPO lists
    - Free block_to_rpo_index map
    - Free the DominanceInfo structure itself

    This prevents memory leaks when dominance info is no longer needed.

    Time complexity: O(n) where n = number of blocks
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Null check
    If info_ptr equals 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get all lists from DominanceInfo
    Let dom_tree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 16
    Let node_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 24
    Let frontiers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 32
    Let frontier_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 40
    Let postorder be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 56
    Let rpo be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 72
    Let block_to_rpo be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with info_ptr, 88

    Note: Free dominance tree nodes and their children lists
    If dom_tree is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than node_count:
            Let node_ptr be proc get from List with dom_tree, i
            Let children_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node_ptr, 16

            Note: Free children list
            If children_list is not equal to 0:
                proc destroy from List with children_list
            End If

            Note: Free node structure
            proc deallocate from Layout with node_ptr, 40

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Free dom_tree list
        proc destroy from List with dom_tree
    End If

    Note: Free frontier sets and their block lists
    If frontiers is not equal to 0:
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than frontier_count:
            Let frontier_set_ptr be proc get from List with frontiers, j
            Let frontier_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 8

            Note: Free frontier blocks list
            If frontier_blocks is not equal to 0:
                proc destroy from List with frontier_blocks
            End If

            Note: Free frontier set structure
            proc deallocate from Layout with frontier_set_ptr, 24

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Note: Free frontiers list
        proc destroy from List with frontiers
    End If

    Note: Free postorder list
    If postorder is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with postorder
    End If

    Note: Free RPO list
    If rpo is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with rpo
    End If

    Note: Free block_to_rpo_index map
    If block_to_rpo is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with block_to_rpo
    End If

    Note: Free DominanceInfo structure itself
    proc deallocate from Layout with info_ptr, 96

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: DOMINANCE MODULE COMPLETE
Note: ============================================================

Note: 
This module provides comprehensive dominance analysis functionality:

PHASE 1: DATA STRUCTURES bitwise and FOUNDATION
- Type definitions: DominanceTreeNode, DominanceFrontierSet, DominanceInfo
- create_dominance_info() - Allocate dominance info structure
- compute_postorder_traversal() - DFS postorder from entry
- compute_reverse_postorder() - Reverse postorder for efficient iteration
- create_block_to_rpo_index_map() - O(1) RPO index lookup
- find_common_dominator() - Intersect operation for Cooper algorithm
- compute_dominance_tree() - Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy algorithm (INDUSTRY STANDARD)

PHASE 2: DOMINANCE QUERIES
- get_immediate_dominator() - Returns idom of a block
- dominates() - Boolean dominance check via chain walking
- strictly_dominates() - Strict dominance (dom ≠ block)
- get_dominated_blocks() - Returns all blocks dominated by given block

PHASE 3: DOMINANCE FRONTIERS (CRITICAL FOR SSA)
- compute_dominance_frontiers() - Cytron et al. 1991 algorithm
- get_dominance_frontier() - Query frontier for specific block
- Enables phi node placement for SSA construction

PHASE 4: POST-DOMINANCE
- Type definition: PostDominanceInfo
- compute_reverse_cfg_postorder() - Postorder on reverse CFG
- compute_post_dominance_tree() - Cooper on reverse CFG
- get_post_dominator() - Returns post-idom
- post_dominates() - Boolean post-dominance check
- Enables control dependence analysis

PHASE 5: VALIDATION bitwise and DEBUG
- validate_dominance_tree() - Verify dominance tree invariants
- print_dominance_tree() - Debug output for visualization
- invalidate_dominance_info() - Invalidate on CFG changes
- destroy_dominance_info() - Complete memory cleanup

Total: 20+ functions across 5 phases
Ready for SSA construction, optimization passes, and code generation

ALGORITHM: Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy (2001) - O(V+E) typical, O(V²) worst case
DOMINANCE FRONTIERS: Cytron et al. (1991) - Classic SSA construction
MEMORY MODEL: TIER 3 (OWNED HEAP) - Permanent structures, deterministic lifetime
APPLICATIONS: SSA construction, loop optimization, dead code elimination, GVN
:End Note